To visualize this concept using TikZ in LaTeX, we can create a timeline diagram showing the sequence of events related to the NMS joining the EU and their subsequent trade access to third-party markets. Here's an example code snippet:

```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=10pt]{standalone}
\usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}

\tikzset{
    timeline/.style={draw=black, thick},
    event/.style={rectangle, draw=blue, fill=blue!30, rounded corners, minimum width=1cm, minimum height=0.5cm},
    text node/.style={align=center, font=\small}
}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[x=1cm, y=0.5cm]

    % Timeline line
    \draw[timeline] (0,-2) -- (8,-2);

    % Events
    \node[event, below left] at (1,-2) {FTA with Mexico};
    \node[event, below right] at (3,-2) {EU Accession};
    \node[event, below right] at (6,-2) {Trade Access};

    % Event labels
    \node[text node, below left=of 1,-2] {2000};
    \node[text node, below right=of 3,-2] {2004};
    \node[text node, below right=of 6,-2] {2004};

    % Connecting lines
    \draw[->, thick, shorten >=2pt, shorten <=2pt] (1,-2) -- (3,-2);
    \draw[->, thick, shorten >=2pt, shorten <=2pt] (3,-2) -- (6,-2);

    % Text annotations
    \node[text node, above=0.5cm of 1,-2] {NMS negotiates FTA with Mexico};
    \node[text node, above=0.5cm of 3,-2] {NMS joins the EU};
    \node[text node, above=0.5cm of 6,-2] {Immediate trade access due to EU membership};

\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

